  "prompt_text": "Prove by induction that the sum of the first n natural numbers is n(n+1)/2.",
  "response_text": "To prove by induction that the sum of the first n natural numbers is n(n+1)/2, we will perform the base case and the inductive step.\n\nBase Case (n = 1):\nThe sum of the first 1 natural number is 1. According to the given formula, n(n+1)/2 for n=1 is 1(1+1)/2 = 1. So, the base case holds true.\n\nInductive Step:\nAssume the formula holds true for some arbitrary positive integer k, i.e., the sum of the first k natural numbers is k(k+1)/2.\n\nNow, we need to show that the formula holds true for k+1, i.e., the sum of the first k+1 natural numbers is (k+1)(k+2)/2.\n\nSum of the first k+1 natural numbers = Sum of the first k natural numbers + (k+1)\n                                                      = k(k+1)/2 + (k+1) (using the inductive assumption)\n                                                      = (k^2 + k)/2 + (k+1)\n                                                      = (k^2 + k + 2k + 2)/2\n                                                      = (k^2 + 3k + 2)/2\n                                                      = (k+1)(k+2)/2\n\nSince the formula holds true for k+1, the inductive step is complete.\n\nBy the principle of mathematical induction, the formula n(n+1)/2 represents the sum of the first n natural numbers for all positive integers n.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 10\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 10\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 10\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 9\nD (Depth of Processing): 10\n---END RATINGS---",
